The Revolution upgrade allows for third-parties to set up subnets, which are (usually) focused on a particular product or function.  This allows the miners to really focus their models for what it is the subnet is doing, rather than trying to be "jacks of all trades".   The subnet owners have to come up with their own codebase for how validation is handled (within the larger, general framework of Bittensor consensus), and in some cases the miners may be much more tailored (for example, I'm pretty sure the storage subnet miners are *very* different, and probably not as intense, as say a miner that's meant to provide multi-modal generative responses).  However, this is me speculating, because I still don't personally understand exactly how the storage subnet works.

You ask "what is the...importance of getting the revolution upgrade solidly in place" and the answer is that it's a major upgrade to the overall network, which expands is capacity, so I would say that it's very important. When you delegate to a validator, the validator is using your Tao to earn additional rewards and increase its position on the network.  The validator does not have access to your staked Tao and cannot take them, even if operating maliciously: your Tao is never forfeited nor are the additional gains you receive in the form of Tao at a rate of 82% of that validator’s rate.

At that point, you can unstake your Tao (including any gains you earned while validator was running) and the validator keeps their portion of the additional gains from your your Tao (18%).
